---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import HeroProject from '../components/HeroProject.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import TopNav from '../components/TopNav.astro';
import ProjectDetails from '../components/ProjectDetails.astro';
import GoogleListings from '../assets/google-listings.png';
import LetroFeatured from '../assets/letro-featured.png';
import DarkTheme from '../assets/dark-theme.png';
import SendButton from '../assets/send-button.png';
import Onboarding from '../assets/onboarding.png';
import LetroIllustrations from '../assets/letro-illustrations.png';
import LetroOnboarding from '../assets/letro-onboarding.png';
import LetroAccount from '../assets/letro-account.png';
import PairContact from '../assets/pair-contact.png';
import Accessibility from '../assets/accessibility.png';


import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
---

<Layout title="Letro app" description="Led the end-to-end UI/UX design and the brand identity of Letro, an offline-compatible alternative to email.">
	<TopNav />
	<HeroProject 
		title="Letro app" 
		subtitle="Led the end-to-end UI/UX design and the brand identity of Letro, an offline-compatible alternative to email."
		imageSrc={LetroFeatured}
		imageAlt="Letro Hero Image"
	/>
	<ProjectDetails 
	tools='Figma, FigmaJam, Maze, Illustrator, AE, Jira, Android Studio. ' 
	timeline='2024' 
	role='I led the UX/UI and brand design for Letro, including:'
	responsibilities={[
        'User research, competitive analysis, and usability testing.',
        'Information architecture and user flows.',
        'Wireframes, hi-fi prototypes, and design system.',
        'Custom illustrations and animations.',
        'Dev-ready documentation.',
        'Close collaboration with the CEO and the lead developer to scope the MVP.'
	]}
    team='UX/UI Designer, CEO and Developer'
	overview={[
		'Letro is an offline alternative to email, designed to circumvent internet shutdowns. Unlike email, Letro offers end-to-end encryption, eliminates phishing and spamming, and users can send and receive messages without access to the Internet.',
	]}
	liveUrl='https://letro.app/en/'
	buttonText='Learn more about Letro'
	/>

    <section class="border-t border-neutral-700 py-8 md:py-16">
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[2fr_3fr] gap-4 md:gap-8">

                    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Problem statement</h2>
                    

                <div>
                    <p>In many regions, traditional messaging tools like Gmail or WhatsApp are rendered useless due to frequent blackouts, surveillance, and censorship. Letro aimed to fill that gap: a secure, offline-compatible alternative that works reliably in such constrained environments.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-neutral-700 py-8 md:py-16">
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[2fr_3fr] gap-4 md:gap-8">
                <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Goals & objetives</h2>
                <div>
                  <p>The challenge was to design a messaging experience that not only works intuitively without the internet for users in regions with heavy Internet restrictions, but also feels secure, trustworthy, and a delight to use.
                  </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-neutral-700 py-8 md:py-16">
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[2fr_3fr] gap-4 md:gap-8">
                <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Research: Understanding users in sensitive contexts</h2>
                
                <div>
                  <p>Due to the sensitive nature of the target audience, I conducted anonymous interviews and user testing with proxy users from targeted regions. This revealed crucial insights:
                  </p>
                  <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-2 ml-4 mt-6">
                    <li>Users were familiar with apps such as Gmail and WhatsApp, but often misinterpreted common UI conventions.</li>
                    <li>Some users expressed significant skepticism toward offline messaging apps due to previous experiences with solutions that failed to work properly offline or had confusing and cluttered interfaces.</li>
                    <li>Many users relied on older Android devices with limited processing power.</li>
                    
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-neutral-700 py-8 md:py-16 space-y-8">
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl font-semibold pb-4">Designing from first principles</h2>
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Addressing technical dependency</h3>
                    <p>Letro works through Awala technology, requiring users to have both apps installed, an important technical dependency that shaped the onboarding experience.</p>
                    <p>Working closely with the CEO and the lead developer, we designed an onboarding flow that automatically detects if Awala is installed, guiding users through the installation process when needed.</p>
                    <p>This approach helped us educate users on the relationship between apps without technical jargon, and reduce installation drop-off through contextual guidance.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <Image src={LetroOnboarding} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">
                <div>
                    <Image src={LetroAccount} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
                <div class="space-y-4 order-first md:order-last">
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Rethinking account creation</h3>
                    <p>In close collaboration with our CEO and lead developer, we designed an innovative simplified onboarding flow that eliminated traditional email/password requirements. Instead, users create accounts with just a username paired with a localised domain (e.g., @guayoyo.cafe in Venezuela). This collaborative approach allowed us to:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-2 pl-4">
                        <li>Creates immediate regional familiarity, making the app feel more personalised.</li>
                        <li>Reduces friction by removing email and password entry.</li>
                        <li>Maintains privacy through anonymised identifiers.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Our shared focus on user-centric design and technical feasibility made this innovative solution possible.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Designing for offline-first experiences</h3>
                    <p>Every interaction had to work seamlessly in both offline and online modes. We couldn't rely on real-time feedback or server validation. Working with the team to understand the technical constraints, we designed for asynchronous sync with clear UI states and user feedback, especially for message delivery and drafts that:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-2 ml-4">
                        <li>Clearly indicate message status (sent/pending/delivered) without requiring connectivity.</li>
                        <li>Provide appropriate feedback during connectivity gaps.</li>
                        <li>Provides a clear call to action for users to try again later.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <Image src={SendButton} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">
                <div class="order-last md:order-first">
                    <Image src={PairContact} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Solving the contact pairing challenge</h3>
                    <p>Unlike email's open sending model, Letro required a contact pairing system before communication. This posed a significant UX challenge, how to make this technical requirement intuitive without adding friction?
                    </p>
                    <p><strong>The solution:</strong> We developed a streamlined pairing flow that visually resembles "adding contacts" in messaging apps rather than email's addressing system, making an unfamiliar concept immediately understandable.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">

                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Clarity over convention
                    </h3>
                    <p>During the user testing, I found that users are very familiar with Gmail and Whatsapp, but some of them found icon-only actions (like the paper plane for "send") confusing.
                    </p>
                    <p>Instead, Letro uses explicit text labels with supporting icons, such as a clearly labeled "Send" and "Reply" button, to reduce ambiguity and support varying levels of digital literacy.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <Image src={SendButton} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">
                <div class="order-last md:order-first">
                    <Image src={Onboarding} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Device constraints
                    </h3>
                    <p>Building Letro meant designing a communication experience from the ground up, without assuming users had fast internet or up-to-date hardware.
                    </p>
                    <p>We ensured Letro could run reliably on older Android phones. This meant lightweight screens, minimal animations, and optimised assets, without compromising clarity or usability.
                    </p>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>


        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[3fr_3fr] gap-8 md:gap-16 items-center">

                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <h3 class="text-xl md:text-[1.6rem] font-semibold">Accessibility & multilingual UX
                    </h3>
                    <p>Letro was localised into multiple languages, so I designed the UI to handle variable-length strings, right-to-left (RTL) support, and font legibility across scripts. I also ensured:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-2 pl-4">
                        <li>High color contrast for readability in harsh lighting.</li>
                        <li>Tap targets large enough for all users.</li>
                        <li>Dark theme to reduce eye strain.</li>
                        <li>Intuitive navigation without relying on icon-only actions.</li> 
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <Image src={Accessibility} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    </section>
    <section class="border-t border-neutral-700 py-8 md:py-16">
        <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto sm:px-6 px-6 lg:px-8">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[2fr_3fr] gap-4 md:gap-8">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl font-semibold">Visual design</h2>
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <p>Letro's visual identity was designed to feel friendly, calm, and trustworthy, qualities often missing in apps associated with surveillance-heavy or politically tense contexts. I created a custom bird mascot to serve as a visual guide throughout the app, adding a layer of warmth and personality to an otherwise serious tool. </p>
                    <p>To support user comfort and extend accessibility, I also designed a fully-compatible dark theme. Both themes adhere to a consistent visual system: clear iconography, generous spacing, and scalable typography, all optimised for low-end Android devices.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-8">
                <Image src={LetroIllustrations} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
            </div>
            
            <div class="mt-8">
                <Image src={DarkTheme} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
            </div>
            <div class="mt-8">
                <Image src={GoogleListings} alt="Natural High Safaris" class="w-full h-auto" />
            </div>
            <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
                <h3 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl font-semibold">Design system</h3>
                <p>To ensure platform-native usability and speed up development, I followed Material Design guidelines throughout the UI, aligning components and interaction patterns with Android standards.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
	
	<Footer />
</Layout>